annotation_title: UK enters national lockdown
annotation_text: The UK enters a second nationwide lockdown. The prime minister, Boris Johnson, says everyone in the four top priority categories will be offered a vaccine by mid-February. The next day, Office for National Statistics data shows that the UK death toll surpassed 100,000: the government's death count, which only includes those deaths occurring within 28 days of a positive Covid test, stood at 81,397.

annotation_title: UK variant could be 30% more deadly, says PM
annotation_text: Johnson says the UK coronavirus variant - later renamed "Alpha" - may be 30% more deadly and warns of stricter travel curbs and continued lockdown. By this date the UK has given a first-dose vaccine to 5.8 million people.

annotation_title: NHS in the grip of a winter crisis
annotation_text: In a sign of the NHS's Covid pressures during winter, new data is released showing that nearly 10% of English NHS trusts had no spare capacity for critical care patients in the final week of January.

annotation_title: Northern Ireland extends lockdown until 1 April
annotation_text: The Stormont executive agrees to extend Northern Ireland’s lockdown to 1 April and a phased return to school for primary aged children followed by secondary level students a few weeks later.

annotation_title: Primary schools and secondary schools reopen
annotation_text: In England, 94% of primary school children and 89% of secondary school students were back in classrooms by 15 March. Scotland and Wales began reopening educational settings at the end of February, while Northern Ireland also waited until early March.

annotation_title: Johnson wishes 'many things' had been done differently
annotation_text: "All I can say is we took all the decisions with the interests of the British people foremost in our hearts and in an effort to protect the public and to prevent death and suffering.”

annotation_title: UK reaches 150,000 deaths by end of March
annotation_text: Guardian analysis shows that the UK death toll had exceeded 150,000 with 54,445 fatalities occurring since the beginning of 2021. This is based on deaths data from the ONS which looks at death certificates.

annotation_title: Pubs and restaurants open outdoors; non-essential shops reopen
annotation_text: Thousands book their first haircut or wrapped up warm for a reunion with friends in a pub garden.

annotation_title: Government offers vaccine to all in 'priority groups'
annotation_text: The government hit its target of offering first jabs to everyone aged 50 or older and those with vulnerabilities by April 15.

annotation_title: UK has world-leading vaccination rate
annotation_text: The UK’s rate of vaccination was the fastest in Europe until the end of April, according to data from Our World in Data.

annotation_title: Majority of new UK cases due to Delta
annotation_text: Public Health England says more than 90% of new UK Covid cases involve the Delta variant. The government faced criticism for not adding India to the red list earlier, after taking the decision on 23 April - two weeks later than Pakistan.

annotation_title: Hancock resigns as health secretary
annotation_text: Matt Hancock resigns days after apologising for kissing his closest aide, Gina Coladangelo, in his ministerial office – in breach of his own Covid-19 rules

annotation_title: UK reintroduces quarantine-free travel
annotation_text: The government announces that quarantine restrictions for people returning to or visiting England from destinations such as Spain, France, Italy, Greece and Germany will be lifted from July 10.

annotation_title: Euros semi-final/final
annotation_text: The final of the Euros between England and Italy was hosted at Wembley. Data later showed that over 5,000 people caught Covid at the Euros final and semi-finals.

annotation_title: Freedom day as 'pingdemic' surges
annotation_text: Almost all restrictions are lifted in England with differing levels of relaxation in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. "Freedom day" was marked by surging cases and the "pingdemic" - almost 700,000 people were pinged by the NHS app in the week to 21 July.

annotation_title: Six EU states overtake UK Covid vaccination rates
annotation_text: According to figures collated by Our World In Data, Malta, Belgium, Spain, Portugal, Denmark and Ireland have all overtaken the UK in terms of the percentages of their populations who are fully vaccinated.

annotation_title: Booster jab rollout begins
annotation_text: NHS started delivering Covid-19 booster jabs to people in eligible groups. This followed JCVI advice that all over-50s and those at greatest risk of the disease should get a third jab to top up their immunity.

annotation_title: Vaccine offered to children aged 12 to 15
annotation_text: Three million 12- to 15-year-olds become eligible to receive the Pfizer vaccine after the UK’s four chief medical officers say they should be offered it on “public health grounds” to "help reduce transmission of Covid-19 in schools”.

annotation_title: Javid warns cases could hit 100k
annotation_text: The health secretary, Sajid Javid, warns that new infections could reach 100,000 a day. On 20 October more than 49,000 new Covid cases were reported in the UK.

annotation_title: Wales makes Covid pass compulsory for large events
annotation_text: People in Wales would need an NHS Covid pass to be able to legally attend large events or nightclubs.

annotation_title: The impact of long Covid
annotation_text: As of 31 October 2021, an estimated 1.2 million people were experiencing self-reported long covid symptoms, according to ONS.

annotation_title: Johnson criticised for sitting maskless beside David Attenborough
annotation_text: The prime minister was criticised for sitting maskless beside 95-year-old David Attenborough during Cop26. Further criticisms emerged later that month when Johnson was photographed without a mask in Hexham hospital, on a Manchester train and during a performance of Macbeth.

annotation_title: Care home workers mandatory jabs
annotation_text: New regulations state that all care home workers, and anyone entering a care home, will need to be fully vaccinated, unless they are exempt under the regulations.

annotation_title: Covid cases surge in Europe
annotation_text: In November a fourth wave of cases sweeps through the continent, and the Netherlands becomes the first western European country to reintroduce partial lockdown after a summer reopening.

annotation_title: Omicron designated 'variant of concern'
annotation_text: WHO classifies new variant first identified in South Africa as Omicron, also describing it as a "variant of concern".

annotation_title: Masks made mandatory in shops and public transport
annotation_text: The government announces that face masks will be made mandatory in shops and on public transport, however hospitality venues remain exempt.

annotation_title: Omicron community transmission confirmed in UK
annotation_text: Sajid Javid confirmed community transmission of the Omicron variant in multiple regions of England, as tighter travel restrictions are brought in.

annotation_title: UK faces a 'tidal wave' of Omicron
annotation_text: Johnson says the UK is facing a "tidal wave" of Omicron. Within 24 hours, the PM confirms that there has been "at least one death" from the variant.

annotation_title: PM faces fresh controversy over another lockdown party
annotation_text: A joint report by the Guardian and Independent newspapers reveals that Johnson attended a pizza party in No 10 Downing Street during the May 2020 lockdown.

annotation_title: Johnson delays restrictions in face of record cases
annotation_text: The Government failed to agree on restrictions that would be imposed before Christmas amid deep cabinet divisions. This follows a spike in cases that saw a record 102,000 cases recorded on 15 December.
